00:36.000 --> 00:38.000
Hello and welcome to Veterans of the Valley.

00:38.000 --> 00:40.000
I'm Tom Turboville.

00:40.000 --> 00:44.000
Last week you met Lieutenant General P.K. Carlton

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
and heard the incredible story of how what he hoped was going to be a career

00:48.000 --> 00:50.000
as an Air Force pilot.

00:50.000 --> 00:53.000
Became instead a career of perhaps even grander service

00:53.000 --> 00:57.000
as a medical surgeon who helped create and implement a vision

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
for landmark breakthroughs in the care and survival of military men and women

01:02.000 --> 01:06.000
who have in the past are now and will certainly in the future

01:06.000 --> 01:09.000
put themselves in harm's way in defense of our country.

01:09.000 --> 01:11.000
We will continue today to hear those stories.

01:11.000 --> 01:17.000
But for most of this 30 minutes, General Carlton will talk about three Navy men,

01:17.000 --> 01:20.000
Craig Powell, Dave Tarantino, and Dave Thomas.

01:20.000 --> 01:24.000
And about a span of 19 minutes when their four paths met

01:24.000 --> 01:29.000
at the Spotted Terrace, flew American Flight 77 into the Pentagon,

01:29.000 --> 01:31.000
11 September 2001.

01:31.000 --> 01:35.000
Please welcome back to Veterans of the Valley, Lieutenant General P.K. Carlton,

01:35.000 --> 01:42.000
who since 2002 has served as director of Homeland Security for the Texas A&M Health Science Center.

01:42.000 --> 01:44.000
General Carlton, welcome back.

01:44.000 --> 01:47.000
It was a fascinating visit that we had last week.

01:47.000 --> 01:50.000
And I want to pick up sort of where we left off.

01:51.000 --> 01:57.000
You have been a medical doctor most of your career after a failed flight physical

01:57.000 --> 02:03.000
said that you could not be a pilot back when you were at the Air Force Academy.

02:03.000 --> 02:07.000
And you decided to become a doctor and that's where your path has taken you.

02:07.000 --> 02:13.000
Talk about in 1999 when you became the 17th Surgeon General of the United States Air Force.

02:13.000 --> 02:15.000
How did your path get there?

02:15.000 --> 02:18.000
And what was your job in Washington at bowling Air Force Base

02:18.000 --> 02:21.000
which right across the street from the Pentagon?

02:21.000 --> 02:24.000
Yes, the Surgeon General of the Air Force is the chief doc for the Air Force,

02:24.000 --> 02:25.000
is the way to think about it.

02:25.000 --> 02:26.000
Right.

02:26.000 --> 02:28.000
Is in charge of organizing and training and equipping.

02:28.000 --> 02:34.000
And so as we look at how the Air Force, the Army, the Navy, each of us does it a little bit differently,

02:34.000 --> 02:37.000
but basically the same, it's how do we present our forces?

02:37.000 --> 02:44.000
My forces indeed were the medical forces that then would support the line of the Army, Navy, and Air Force.

02:44.000 --> 02:49.000
And my particular part of the Air was air evacuation.

02:49.000 --> 02:50.000
Right.

02:50.000 --> 02:51.000
And so that was my job.

02:51.000 --> 02:56.000
It also involved how do we do peace-time health care, how do we balance a budget, how do we interact with the Congress,

02:56.000 --> 03:01.000
a whole variety of other things, but it was to look around the corners for what's coming in the future,

03:01.000 --> 03:07.000
how can we prepare for them, and then to execute the medical program for 79 different facilities,

03:07.000 --> 03:10.000
which we had throughout the United States and overseas at that time.

03:10.000 --> 03:11.000
Right.

03:11.000 --> 03:16.000
You told me at one time, when we were visiting that back in the 90s, there were people that were saying,

03:16.000 --> 03:19.000
hey, you know, we're not going to need this, we're not going to go to war again.

03:19.000 --> 03:25.000
And then in 2001, 2002, that all changed, of course.

03:25.000 --> 03:31.000
And in February of 2001, February of 2001, we're talking now.

03:31.000 --> 03:36.000
I want you to talk about a discussion that you were having with a colleague in the Pentagon.

03:36.000 --> 03:38.000
And the discussion came to mind.

03:38.000 --> 03:43.000
And this goes back to what we were talking about last week about how you described your job as looking around corners,

03:43.000 --> 03:46.000
conceiving of the inconceivable.

03:46.000 --> 03:54.000
And sort of how that relates to just sort of the happenstance conversation, how it came about one day in February of 2001.

03:54.000 --> 03:57.000
Well, I was walking from one place to another, and the clinic commander,

03:57.000 --> 04:01.000
where the Pentagon Clinic came up to me and said, we've got to do an exercise.

04:01.000 --> 04:06.000
And he started to describe what his plans were, and then he had to be quiet,

04:06.000 --> 04:10.000
because we had an airplane go overhead, and we couldn't hear each other.

04:10.000 --> 04:14.000
And he looked at me and said, well, why don't we just do an airplane, hits the Pentagon?

04:14.000 --> 04:18.000
Loses an engine on takeoff from Ronald Reagan, the North airport.

04:18.000 --> 04:21.000
Takes a bunch of birds, it's not a far out scenario.

04:21.000 --> 04:26.000
And crashes with a minimal controllable airspeed into the Pentagon, medics you're up.

04:26.000 --> 04:28.000
I said, I'll buy. Please do.

04:28.000 --> 04:34.000
And so that exercise we accomplished in May, we did it as a tabletop, we had pictures of it.

04:34.000 --> 04:39.000
The airplane came to rest in the Cingric Court yard, and we learned a number of lessons.

04:39.000 --> 04:43.000
We, number one, didn't evacuate well, we didn't have a good evacuation plan.

04:43.000 --> 04:46.000
We didn't have evacuation plans for our special needs people.

04:46.000 --> 04:49.000
We didn't have equipment, we didn't have training.

04:49.000 --> 04:53.000
We didn't have a variety of things that we needed for our medical teams that we thought we should need.

04:53.000 --> 04:56.000
And we decided that our get well date would be one September.

04:56.000 --> 04:57.000
Right.

04:57.000 --> 05:06.000
So when the event occurred on 11 September, I was in my boss's office, the vice chief staff,

05:06.000 --> 05:11.000
and went down to the clinic to pick up a medical team thinking that the toughest place to be

05:11.000 --> 05:15.000
would be in the Cingric Court yard because you couldn't get out.

05:15.000 --> 05:20.000
And as I grabbed a protective vest to put on, the young man beside me said,

05:20.000 --> 05:23.000
General, why are you making us do this again?

05:23.000 --> 05:28.000
Now you don't normally get challenged by a two striper at a three star level,

05:28.000 --> 05:32.000
but I responded to him and he said, well, I'm not making you do it again.

05:32.000 --> 05:34.000
Did you learn something last time?

05:34.000 --> 05:36.000
He said, yeah, I know how to handle this.

05:36.000 --> 05:40.000
I said great, and stick like glue to me, because this is the real thing.

05:40.000 --> 05:42.000
Take a deep breath. That's real smoke.

05:42.000 --> 05:43.000
This is for real.

05:43.000 --> 05:46.000
And in fact, that young man put me out when I caught on fire.

05:46.000 --> 05:48.000
I want to back up just a second.

05:49.000 --> 05:51.000
You arrived to work that day.

05:51.000 --> 05:53.000
You get your figure to be a normal day of work.

05:53.000 --> 05:56.000
You had your list of things to do, what you were going to accomplish that day.

05:56.000 --> 06:01.000
And I think you said that you were in a meeting of some sort at the time,

06:01.000 --> 06:04.000
when somebody turned on the television.

06:04.000 --> 06:11.000
And you said that immediately you knew where most of the country, most of the media,

06:11.000 --> 06:15.000
when the first plane hit the first tower in New York, that the people in that room knew

06:16.000 --> 06:20.000
that that was not a system that had accidentally hit the World Trade Center.

06:20.000 --> 06:21.000
You knew more than that.

06:21.000 --> 06:25.000
Yes. In that room, which was the chief of staff, the vice chief,

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
all of the senior Air Force people in the Washington DC area,

06:28.000 --> 06:30.000
it was very obvious that was no accident.

06:30.000 --> 06:32.000
That was not an navigational error.

06:32.000 --> 06:33.000
Yes.

06:33.000 --> 06:34.000
And that we had a real problem.

06:34.000 --> 06:39.000
They did not interrupt the meeting immediately, but instead waited a couple of minutes,

06:39.000 --> 06:42.000
and so literally we watched that one, the first impact,

06:42.000 --> 06:46.000
and then real footage came through the show, the second impact on the second tower.

06:46.000 --> 06:47.000
Exactly.

06:47.000 --> 06:50.000
And so at that point, our boss said, General Manor at War,

06:50.000 --> 06:53.000
and it was very apparent that we had a problem.

06:53.000 --> 06:54.000
Right.

06:54.000 --> 06:55.000
Indeed.

06:55.000 --> 07:00.000
You were on the other side of the Pentagon, from the impact area,

07:00.000 --> 07:04.000
but you knew immediately because you said that you could feel the vibration,

07:04.000 --> 07:05.000
you could feel the shutter.

07:05.000 --> 07:06.000
Yes.

07:06.000 --> 07:09.000
And the smoke was coming through the air conditioning system.

07:09.000 --> 07:10.000
Yes.

07:10.000 --> 07:13.000
On the opposite side of the Pentagon, more than a half a mile away,

07:13.000 --> 07:17.000
the Pentagon shook from the impact, and the smoke spread immediately.

07:17.000 --> 07:19.000
And so we knew we had a problem.

07:19.000 --> 07:20.000
Right.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
Take it from there.

07:23.000 --> 07:28.000
You went to the center of the courtyard with the team, reported to the fire chief.

07:28.000 --> 07:32.000
I'm ready to accept casualties, because as your job,

07:32.000 --> 07:35.000
